title: For Sale:  Sold
postcontent:
NATO CZ P-01 (9mm) for sale with 5 mags, (3 high cap and 2 standard) just an awesome piece! If you have never shot a CZ you need to! This comes with 5 Mags, night sights and is in very good condition. If you dont know anything about CZ you should def look them up.  

The NATO P-01 is based on the CZ 75, the most used service pistol in the world. Over 60 countries use it as the standard side arm of their Armies, National police forces, National security agencies or other Law enforcement organizations. No other pistol can make this claim.

The NATO CZ P-01 is the culmination of several years of exhaustive design and testing. Ceska Zbrojovka has always had some of the most rigorous testing requirements in the world but, the Czech National police has required that they go even further, the testing regiment for this new pistol was the most demanding anyone has ever encountered. There are almost 20 specific requirements covering everything from accuracy to interchangability, from safety to reliability/durability and everything in between.

THE REQUIREMENTS THIS GUN WENT THROUGH TO GET NATO APPROVED:


The pistol must be 100% reliable in extreme conditions, the following is a list of some of the minimum requirements.

Must be able to complete the following without failure:

4000 dry firings 
3000 De-cockings
Operator level disassembly 1350 times with out ware or damage to components.
Complete disassembly 150 times, this is all the way down, pins, springs etc.
100% interchangability, any number of pistols randomly selected, disassembled, parts mixed and reassembled with no failures of any kind including loss of accuracy.


Safety requirements:

Drop test
1.5 meter (4.9”) drop test, this is done 54 times with the pistol loaded (blank) and the hammer cocked. Dropping the pistol on the butt, the muzzle, back of the slide, sides of the gun, top of the slide, in essence, any angle that you could drop the gun from. This is done on concrete and 0 failures are allowed! A failure is the gun firing.

3meter drop (9.8”) 5 times with the pistol loaded (blank) and the hammer cocked, This is done on concrete and 0 failures are allowed! A failure is the gun firing.

After these tests are complete the gun must fire without service.

The factory contracted an independent lab to do additional testing on guns that previously passed the drop tests. These pistol were dropped an additional 352 times without failure.

The pistol must also complete an environmental conditions test: 
This means cold, heat, dust/sand and mud.
The pistol must fire after being frozen for 24 hours at –35C (-36F).
The pistol must fire after being heated for 24 hours at 70C (126F)
The pistol must fire after being submerged in mud, sand and combinations including being stripped of oil then completing the sand and mud tests again.

Service life:
The service life requirement from the Czech police was 15,000 rounds of +P ammo!
The pistol will exceed 30,000 rounds with ball 9mm.

Reliability:
The reliability requirements for the P-01 pistol are 99.8%, that’s a .2% failure rate. 
This equals 20 stoppages in 10,000 rounds or 500 “Mean Rounds Between Failure” (MRBF) 
During testing, the average number of stoppages was only 7 per 15,000 rounds fired, this is a .05% failure rate, a MRBF rate of 2142 rounds! Over 4 time the minimum acceptable requirement.
The U.S. Army MRBF requirement is 495 rounds for 9mm pistols with 115 grain

title: For Trade:  Authentic Indian Artifacts - stone, flint, etc.
postcontent:
I have authentic Indian Artifacts (no repros) that I'd consider trading towards guns. I have axes, banners, pipes, clovis and dovetail points/arrowheads; you name it. Most will have authentication papers from top authenticators. Sorry to all the sharks; I know their value and what they're worth so look elsewhere for victims. Before responding please familiarize yourself a bit with types/conditions/and values so you're not shocked. I have many that are valued in the hundreds of dollars on up into the thousands. I will trade them at fair market values, in the ballpark of Overstreet's price guide values. 

Like guns, these ancient tools & weapons have always been good investments, hold their value well, increase in value over time and are lots of fun to collect.

Please contact me if interested. You need to let me know what you have to trade or I probably won't respond. I will be glad to send pictures and descriptions of my items but I may ask to see yours first so I can make offers within a particular price range (ie; if you have a $600 gun I can show you some $600 pieces). I might trade higher-in-value items for a gun I really like.  

I like modern guns mainly but will consider any type.

title: For Sale:  VERY NICE Saiga 12 Russian, mag fed, semi-auto, 12ga shotgun.
postcontent:
VERY NICE Izhmash imported Russian Saiga 12 semi-auto, magazine fed, gas operated 12ga shotgun for sale.

-Has been FULLY 922r compliance converted as you can see; The FCG (fire control group) has been moved forward. There has also been a gas port modification made to the shotgun porting the holes in the barrel into the gas block from .074" to .096" (3 of them) opening up the ports to allow for MUCCCH better reliability with light loads like birdshot. Will fire ANYTHING you put through this thing 3" length or smaller. Factory unconverted (and some that have not had the gas port mod) Saiga 12's have LOTS of issues with FTE (failure to eject) with light loads like birdshot because it doesn't have enough to ummphh to kick the bolt carrier back far enough to cycle the next shell. That is NOT a problem with this gun.

-SUPER RELIABLE. Has MD Arms (premiere) 5 setting gas regulator, Krebs Custom Combat Shotgun Sight and Krebs Custom rear wide combat peep sight. Comes with factory Izhmash 5 round magazine. FCG is Tapco G2 and very smoooth and real LIGHT trigger. Warsaw length AK stock and S.A.W. style pistol grip. This thing is loaded with aftermarket options and comes with factory OEM Russian stock and hand guard. Also has gas tube heat shield (very nice looking). I am asking $1000 for this shotgun because of the work, time and $ I have put into it.

Also has CSS billet trigger guard, comfortable Russian style (grenade launcher) slip on butt pad. This thing is awesome. Will fire as fast as your trigger finger can pull and cycle every shell. Does not come with a muzzle brake although it is threaded and ready for any kind available for this gun (there are LOTS). I also have lost the AR15 style sight post that goes in the Krebs Custom Combat Shotgun Sight housing. Is threaded for and will take ANY AR style sight post.






I'll even throw in a 6 point collapsible M4/AR style stock that will fit it.

title: For Sale:  VERY NICE Saiga 12 Russian, mag fed, semi-auto, 12ga shotgun.
postcontent:
VERY NICE Izhmash imported Russian Saiga 12 semi-auto, magazine fed, gas operated 12ga shotgun for sale.

-Has been FULLY 922r compliance converted as you can see; The FCG (fire control group) has been moved forward. There has also been a gas port modification made to the shotgun porting the holes in the barrel into the gas block from .074" to .096" (3 of them) opening up the ports to allow for MUCCCH better reliability with light loads like birdshot. Will fire ANYTHING you put through this thing 3" length or smaller. Factory unconverted (and some that have not had the gas port mod) Saiga 12's have LOTS of issues with FTE (failure to eject) with light loads like birdshot because it doesn't have enough to ummphh to kick the bolt carrier back far enough to cycle the next shell. That is NOT a problem with this gun.

-SUPER RELIABLE. Has MD Arms (premiere) 5 setting gas regulator, Krebs Custom Combat Shotgun Sight and Krebs Custom rear wide combat peep sight. Comes with factory Izhmash 5 round magazine. FCG is Tapco G2 and very smoooth and real LIGHT trigger. Warsaw length AK stock and S.A.W. style pistol grip. This thing is loaded with aftermarket options and comes with factory OEM Russian stock and hand guard. Also has gas tube heat shield (very nice looking). I am asking $1000 for this shotgun because of the work, time and $ I have put into it.

Also has CSS billet trigger guard, comfortable Russian style (grenade launcher) slip on butt pad. This thing is awesome. Will fire as fast as your trigger finger can pull and cycle every shell. Does not come with a muzzle brake although it is threaded and ready for any kind available for this gun (there are LOTS). I also have lost the AR15 style sight post that goes in the Krebs Custom Combat Shotgun Sight housing. Is threaded for and will take ANY AR style sight post.






I'll even throw in a 6 point collapsible M4/AR style stock that will fit it. 




Contact JJ if interested.

title: For Sale:  1967 F100 BLUE / WHITE 67 F100 STYLESIDE SHORTBED - 65136 ORG MILES - 300 INLINE 6
postcontent:
Will take M4 variant as partial payment.

This is a 1967 Ford F100 Styleside Shortbed with a 300 inline engine with 65136 ORIGINAL MILES.  I am the third owner of this truck and purchased this truck in February of 2008 as my daily driver.  When I bought the truck it had 61,084 miles.  During the four years I owned it I NEVER had a problem with it. I believe I am the third owner.  The person I bought it from said he was the second owner and that he bought it from his neighbor.  He said the engine was rebuilt in 2005ish.

Over the four years I had it, I changed the oil regularly, replaced the battery, cleaned the fuel tank, replaced the fuel filter, replaced the entire front drum brakes (drums, shoes, springs and cylinders), plugs and points, and a handful of hoses along the way.

Obviously as a 45 year old truck it has some wear, but it is a beautiful truck and I can't go anywhere without getting compliments on it.  I have had many offers on it over the years (including a straight trade on my bosses jeep that he later sold for $11,000), but now I am ready to sell it.  I never planned on selling it, but after moving to North Carolina other hobbies have taken my time and I just don't drive it like I used to nor do I have the time and money to do the things to it I would like to.

This is a wonderful daily driver and a great project truck.  If you look at the pictures you will notice the wood bed.  The steel bed underneath is solid, but was a pretty banged up.   I always wanted a wood bed, and this was a proof of concept. Three and a half years ago it looked stunning.  If I had to do it over again, I would do some things differently in the type of wood I used, but as a $350 proof of concept it worked great.  I can show you pictures of how it looked when I first installed it, if you want to get an idea of what the potential is.

I am not a mechanic - but this truck is extremely easy to work on and was a lot of fun. I have lots of parts I am including.  Here is a rough list.

-All three shop manuals in PDF Format on CD.
-Mirrors

This really is a beautiful truck

title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Official Police .38 special revolver 6" barrel
postcontent:
Colt 'Official Police' model in the common .38 special caliber.

For the unfamiliar, this is the larger framed Colt model introduced in 1927. The basic design had been around since about 1900, and it saw both police and military use until the Official Police ended production in 1969. This is not the smaller 'Police Positive,' which was was also available in .38 and is more commonly seen with a short barrel. Both guns are often referred to as 'police specials.'

This particular piece was made in the late 50's, and features the traditional Colt blued finish and original real wood grips. Original 6" barrel.

Functionally the gun is great. Cylinder locks in tight, firing pin is in good shape. Double action trigger pull is very smooth. Firing it single action is also nice, but you need to be careful- once the hammer is cocked, it takes a very light touch of the trigger to drop it. To me, that's a good thing...it's a good safe revolver with a trusty DA, but also an excellent target plinker when you use it in SA. Barrel/rifling is pristine and this gun is very accurate.

As far as looks go, there is a lot of bluing remaining, but the gun exhibits the typical holster wear of a used service revolver. Most notably, the right side grip has been worn smoother than the left, and there are worn spots on the outside of the barrel from going in and out of the holster.

I'm asking $435 or best offer.
